profile_1993_llama3.2:3b.think_process:
Politics? It's like, I know it's supposed to be about making our country better, but sometimes it feels like just a bunch of rich people arguing and not really doing anything for us common folks. My husband works hard every day, just to make ends meet, and I do my part too, taking care of the kids and managing the household. We don't need all those politicians telling us what to do. Sometimes it seems like they're more interested in lining their own pockets than helping people like us.

I remember when I was younger, things seemed different. There were real leaders who cared about the people, but now...now I just see a lot of corruption and lies. My cousin's friend is a policeman, and he says that sometimes it feels like politicians are more powerful than the law itself. It doesn't fill me with confidence.

I wish someone would explain to me what politics really means for my daily life, but whenever I try to talk to people about it, they just give me a tired look or tell me to stop worrying and focus on my family. Like, I am worried! I want to know who's going to protect our rights and make sure we can afford healthcare when we need it.

My father was a worker, not a politician, and he always said the same thing: "No se mete en los asuntos de nadie". I mean, why bother with all those politicians and their promises when we already have problems to solve here in our daily lives? Like how can I provide for my family on a fixed salary? How can I get ahead in this economy? That's what matters to me. Sometimes, if I'm watching the news, it's just background noise. Other times, it might interest me if there's something specific going on that affects my life directly... but generally?

profile_2007_llama3.2:3b.think_process:
Politics is something that happens on a national level, but it rarely affects my daily life. I work hard every day to provide for my family and make ends meet. The government should be involved in providing basic services like education and healthcare, but when it comes to local issues, I trust my neighbors and the community leaders to handle things.

I do keep up with some of the major news outlets, just enough to stay informed about what's happening in the country. But personally, politics isn't something that gets me excited or engaged. I'd rather focus on improving my own life and contributing to my community than getting involved in partisan debates.
